    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-10-26T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-10-26T16:00:00-05:00" n="787"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d787">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">822.51 Et 3/6: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bading</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-10-26T16:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 26, 1923—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>15. Your telegrams 12, 13, 14.<note n="16" xml:id="d787fn16">Telegrams nos. 12
                        and 13 not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Please address following letter to the President: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Under instructions from my Government I desire to point out to Your
                            Excellency that the loan contract, as I understand, does not in its
                            present form contain any provision for the payment of the debt of the
                            Agricultural Association to the Mercantile Bank. The Government of the
                            United States, however, has carefully noted the assurances contained in
                            your letter of February 5, 1922, to Minister Hartman <pb facs="1050"
                                n="934" xml:id="pg_934"/> that ‘If the Government secures a foreign
                            loan it will immediately pay half of the credit of the abovementioned
                                bank.’<note n="18" xml:id="d787fn18">Not printed.</note> My
                            Government is therefore confident that, although the loan contract
                            contains no provision on this subject, the Government of Ecuador will
                            immediately meet half of the indebtedness in question in the event of
                            procuring a foreign loan, and I have therefore been instructed to bring
                            this matter to Your Excellency’s attention and to request that I be
                            advised of the measures that your Government proposes to take in
                            conformity with the assurances heretofore given.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Report President’s reply by cable.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
